		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">thenewguy wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I really like NES Metal Gear. I grew up playing that game, and it was a lot of fun.<br /><br />Anyway, good luck with the game. It'd be cool to see something like this on the NES!</div><br /><br />I enjoyed it, too, but it is certainly not without its flaws. If you liked the first NES <em>Metal Gear</em>, you'd likely love <em>Snake's Revenge</em>.<br /><br />And thank you! I'm currently debating the sheer foundation of what the game will be built on, whether it will be a NES game, a NES-styled game, a Genesis game, a Genesis-styled game, or perhaps a <a href="http://www.retrovgs.com/projects.html" class="postlink">Coleco Chameleon</a> game (assuming the console does well). Other things like appropriating funds (Kickstarter, IndieGoGo, Patreon, etc.), finding programmers after having gathered enough money to pay them, advertising, and selling the game to vendors like Piko Interactive, Stone Age Gamer, and so on are all problems I should start thinking about but not necessarily worry about.

		

